{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: 'Chapter 8. Partial Derivatives and the Gradient'\n",
        "subtitle: 'Coordinate rates of change, sensitivity, and local information'\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Chapter overview\n",
        "\n",
        "A function of one variable has one basic input direction: move left or move right on the number line. A function of several variables has many input directions. The first step is to measure change in the coordinate directions.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a function $f(x,y)$, the partial derivative $f_x$ measures the instantaneous rate of change when $x$ changes and $y$ is held fixed. The partial derivative $f_y$ measures the instantaneous rate of change when $y$ changes and $x$ is held fixed. These two numbers are not separate facts. Together they form the **gradient vector**\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x,y)=\\langle f_x(x,y), f_y(x,y)\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The gradient is the local direction-information vector for a scalar field. It tells us how the output changes to first order near a point, how level curves are oriented, and how a loss function changes when model parameters change. This is why gradients appear everywhere in applied mathematics, statistics, machine learning, optimization, physics, imaging, and AI.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note title='Teaching-material connection'}\n",
        "This chapter develops the MATH 2321 material on partial derivatives, geometric traces, numerical derivative estimates, second partial derivatives, Clairaut's theorem, and the gradient vector. It also uses the MATH 5002 perspective that partial derivatives reduce multivariable differentiation to single-variable differentiation by holding all other variables fixed.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Learning goals\n",
        "\n",
        "After studying this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. define $f_x(a,b)$ and $f_y(a,b)$ using limits;\n",
        "2. interpret partial derivatives as slopes of coordinate traces of a surface;\n",
        "3. compute partial derivatives by treating other variables as constants;\n",
        "4. estimate partial derivatives from data or finite differences;\n",
        "5. compute second partial derivatives and mixed partial derivatives;\n",
        "6. use Clairaut's theorem when mixed partial derivatives are continuous;\n",
        "7. compute the gradient of functions on $\\mathbb R^2$, $\\mathbb R^3$, and $\\mathbb R^n$;\n",
        "8. explain why the gradient is perpendicular to level curves and level surfaces;\n",
        "9. connect gradients with sensitivity analysis, image processing, statistics, and machine learning.\n",
        "\n",
        "Python resources for this chapter:\n",
        "\n",
        "- [Chapter 8 Python lab](../labs/MATH2321_Chapter08_Partial_Derivatives_and_the_Gradient.ipynb)\n",
        "- [Chapter 8 interactive HTML page](../htmls/chapter-08.html)\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.1 From one derivative to many partial derivatives\n",
        "\n",
        "For a single-variable function $y=f(x)$, the derivative at $x=a$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f'(a)=\\lim_{h\\to 0}\\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Geometrically, this is the slope of the tangent line at $x=a$. For a two-variable function $z=f(x,y)$, the graph is a surface. At a point $(a,b,f(a,b))$, there are many possible curves on the surface passing through that point. The easiest curves are the two coordinate traces:\n",
        "\n",
        "- the trace obtained by fixing $y=b$ and allowing $x$ to vary;\n",
        "- the trace obtained by fixing $x=a$ and allowing $y$ to vary.\n",
        "\n",
        "The slopes of these two traces are the partial derivatives.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important title='Core idea'}\n",
        "A partial derivative is an ordinary derivative applied to a slice of a multivariable function.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.2 Definitions of $f_x$ and $f_y$\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $f$ be a function of two variables. The partial derivative of $f$ with respect to $x$ at $(a,b)$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(a,b)=\\lim_{h\\to 0}\\frac{f(a+h,b)-f(a,b)}{h},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "provided the limit exists.\n",
        "\n",
        "The partial derivative of $f$ with respect to $y$ at $(a,b)$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(a,b)=\\lim_{h\\to 0}\\frac{f(a,b+h)-f(a,b)}{h},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "provided the limit exists.\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently, define\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "g(x)=f(x,b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(a,b)=g'(a).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Similarly, if\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "k(y)=f(a,y),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(a,b)=k'(b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The notation is flexible. If $z=f(x,y)$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x=\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}=\\frac{\\partial z}{\\partial x}=D_xf,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y=\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}=\\frac{\\partial z}{\\partial y}=D_yf.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip title='How to compute partial derivatives'}\n",
        "To compute $f_x$, treat $y$ as a constant and differentiate with respect to $x$. To compute $f_y$, treat $x$ as a constant and differentiate with respect to $y$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.3 Geometric interpretation: slopes of traces\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose the surface is $z=f(x,y)$ and we focus on the point $(a,b,f(a,b))$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The trace in the plane $y=b$ is the single-variable curve\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(x,b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Its tangent slope at $x=a$ is $f_x(a,b)$. The trace in the plane $x=a$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(a,y),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and its tangent slope at $y=b$ is $f_y(a,b)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.1: A surface and its coordinate traces\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=4-\\frac{x^2}{4}-y^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a downward-opening elliptic paraboloid. At the point $(1,1)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(x,y)=-\\frac{x}{2},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(x,y)=-2y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(1,1)=-\\frac12,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(1,1)=-2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Interpretation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- if $y=1$ is held fixed and $x$ increases near $x=1$, the height decreases at rate $1/2$;\n",
        "- if $x=1$ is held fixed and $y$ increases near $y=1$, the height decreases at rate $2$."
      ],
      "id": "6a06e7d0"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch08-surface-traces\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Coordinate traces of $f(x,y)=4-x^2/4-y^2$ through the point $(1,1)$. The partial derivatives are slopes of these traces.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(-4, 4, 120)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(-2.2, 2.2, 120)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "Z = 4 - X**2/4 - Y**2\n",
        "\n",
        "a, b = 1.0, 1.0\n",
        "z0 = 4 - a**2/4 - b**2\n",
        "\n",
        "fig = plt.figure()\n",
        "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, alpha=0.45, linewidth=0)\n",
        "\n",
        "x_trace = np.linspace(-4, 4, 200)\n",
        "y_trace = np.linspace(-2.2, 2.2, 200)\n",
        "ax.plot(x_trace, b*np.ones_like(x_trace), 4 - x_trace**2/4 - b**2, linewidth=3)\n",
        "ax.plot(a*np.ones_like(y_trace), y_trace, 4 - a**2/4 - y_trace**2, linewidth=3)\n",
        "ax.scatter([a], [b], [z0], s=60)\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('x')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('y')\n",
        "ax.set_zlabel('z')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Surface with coordinate traces')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch08-surface-traces",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 8.4 Computing partial derivatives\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.2: Polynomial, trigonometric, and exponential terms\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=x^3+x^2\\sin y-xe^y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "To compute $f_x$, hold $y$ constant:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(x,y)=3x^2+2x\\sin y-e^y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "To compute $f_y$, hold $x$ constant:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(x,y)=x^2\\cos y-xe^y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(1,2)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(1,2)=3+2\\sin 2-e^2,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(1,2)=\\cos 2-e^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.3: A radial function\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For $(x,y)\\ne(0,0)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(x,y)=\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(x,y)=\\frac{y}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(1,2)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(1,2)=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt5},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(1,2)=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt5}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At the origin, the formula is not valid because the denominator is zero. In fact, $f_x(0,0)$ and $f_y(0,0)$ exist, but the function is not differentiable at the origin. This reminds us that partial derivatives are only coordinate-direction information. They are important, but not always the whole story.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.5 Partial derivatives from data\n",
        "\n",
        "In applications, we often do not know a formula for $f$. We may only have sampled values. Then partial derivatives are estimated by finite differences.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, if we know $f(1,2)$, $f(1.1,2)$, and $f(1,2.15)$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(1,2)\\approx \\frac{f(1.1,2)-f(1,2)}{0.1},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(1,2)\\approx \\frac{f(1,2.15)-f(1,2)}{0.15}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This idea is fundamental in numerical differentiation, image processing, computer vision, and machine learning.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.4: Finite-difference estimates\n",
        "\n",
        "Use\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=x^3+x^2\\sin y-xe^y\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and estimate $f_x(1,2)$ and $f_y(1,2)$ using forward differences."
      ],
      "id": "18dc64e5"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: tbl-ch08-finite-difference-estimates\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def f(x, y):\n",
        "    return x**3 + x**2*np.sin(y) - x*np.exp(y)\n",
        "\n",
        "point = (1.0, 2.0)\n",
        "hx = 0.1\n",
        "hy = 0.15\n",
        "\n",
        "fx_forward = (f(point[0] + hx, point[1]) - f(*point)) / hx\n",
        "fy_forward = (f(point[0], point[1] + hy) - f(*point)) / hy\n",
        "\n",
        "fx_exact = 3*point[0]**2 + 2*point[0]*np.sin(point[1]) - np.exp(point[1])\n",
        "fy_exact = point[0]**2*np.cos(point[1]) - point[0]*np.exp(point[1])\n",
        "\n",
        "print('Forward estimate for f_x(1,2):', fx_forward)\n",
        "print('Exact value of f_x(1,2):       ', fx_exact)\n",
        "print('Forward estimate for f_y(1,2):', fy_forward)\n",
        "print('Exact value of f_y(1,2):       ', fy_exact)"
      ],
      "id": "tbl-ch08-finite-difference-estimates",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Forward differences are simple, but they are not always very accurate. A better estimate often uses the centered difference\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(a,b)\\approx \\frac{f(a+h,b)-f(a-h,b)}{2h}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The same idea works for $f_y$."
      ],
      "id": "0997991a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 4.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch08-finite-difference-error\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Centered differences usually converge faster than forward differences for smooth functions.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def f_num(x, y):\n",
        "    return x**3 + x**2*np.sin(y) - x*np.exp(y)\n",
        "\n",
        "x0, y0 = 1.0, 2.0\n",
        "exact = 3*x0**2 + 2*x0*np.sin(y0) - np.exp(y0)\n",
        "h_values = 10.0**(-np.arange(1, 9))\n",
        "forward_errors = []\n",
        "centered_errors = []\n",
        "\n",
        "for h in h_values:\n",
        "    forward = (f_num(x0+h, y0) - f_num(x0, y0)) / h\n",
        "    centered = (f_num(x0+h, y0) - f_num(x0-h, y0)) / (2*h)\n",
        "    forward_errors.append(abs(forward - exact))\n",
        "    centered_errors.append(abs(centered - exact))\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "ax.loglog(h_values, forward_errors, marker='o', label='forward difference')\n",
        "ax.loglog(h_values, centered_errors, marker='o', label='centered difference')\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('step size h')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('absolute error')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Finite-difference error for f_x(1,2)')\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "ax.grid(True, which='both', alpha=0.3)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch08-finite-difference-error",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 8.6 Image processing interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "An image can be viewed as a function\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "I(x,y)=\\text{pixel intensity at location }(x,y).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then $I_x$ measures horizontal change and $I_y$ measures vertical change. Large values of $|I_x|$ or $|I_y|$ often indicate edges. This is the same calculus idea, but applied to a matrix of data instead of a symbolic formula."
      ],
      "id": "16b4cc6d"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 8,
        "fig-height": 4.5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch08-image-gradient\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Finite differences applied to image-like data. Horizontal and vertical derivatives reveal edges.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "n = 120\n",
        "x = np.linspace(-1, 1, n)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(-1, 1, n)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "image = np.exp(-8*((X+0.35)**2 + (Y-0.1)**2)) + 0.75*np.exp(-18*((X-0.3)**2 + (Y+0.25)**2))\n",
        "image += 0.15*(X > 0.1)\n",
        "\n",
        "dy, dx = np.gradient(image, y, x)\n",
        "grad_mag = np.sqrt(dx**2 + dy**2)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(11, 3.5))\n",
        "axes[0].imshow(image, origin='lower', extent=[-1, 1, -1, 1])\n",
        "axes[0].set_title('image intensity I')\n",
        "axes[1].imshow(dx, origin='lower', extent=[-1, 1, -1, 1])\n",
        "axes[1].set_title('horizontal derivative I_x')\n",
        "axes[2].imshow(grad_mag, origin='lower', extent=[-1, 1, -1, 1])\n",
        "axes[2].set_title('gradient magnitude')\n",
        "for ax in axes:\n",
        "    ax.set_xticks([])\n",
        "    ax.set_yticks([])\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch08-image-gradient",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: {.callout-note title='Modern interpretation'}\n",
        "In symbolic calculus, $f_x$ and $f_y$ are formulas. In data analysis, they are often approximations computed from samples, grids, or pixels. The concept is the same: measure local change in coordinate directions.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.7 Second partial derivatives\n",
        "\n",
        "Partial derivatives can be differentiated again. If $z=f(x,y)$, then the four second partial derivatives are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{xx}=\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}\\left(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}\\right),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_{xy}=\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y}\\left(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}\\right),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{yx}=\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x}\\left(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}\\right),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_{yy}=\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y}\\left(\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}\\right).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The derivatives $f_{xy}$ and $f_{yx}$ are called **mixed partial derivatives**.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.5: Second partials and mixed partials\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=x^2+xy^3+\\sin(xy).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "First derivatives:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x=2x+y^3+y\\cos(xy),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y=3xy^2+x\\cos(xy).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Second derivatives:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{xx}=2-y^2\\sin(xy),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{xy}=3y^2+\\cos(xy)-xy\\sin(xy),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{yx}=3y^2+\\cos(xy)-xy\\sin(xy),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{yy}=6xy-x^2\\sin(xy).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Here the mixed partial derivatives are equal.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.8 Clairaut's theorem\n",
        "\n",
        "The equality $f_{xy}=f_{yx}$ is common, but it is not automatic for every possible function. The standard theorem is the following.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important title='Clairaut theorem'}\n",
        "Suppose $f$ is defined on a disk containing $(a,b)$. If $f_{xy}$ and $f_{yx}$ are both continuous on that disk, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_{xy}(a,b)=f_{yx}(a,b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "In most elementary examples involving polynomials, exponentials, logarithms, and trigonometric functions on regions where the formulas are defined, the continuity hypothesis is satisfied. Then the order of mixed partial differentiation can be switched.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.9 The gradient vector\n",
        "\n",
        "The first partial derivatives form a vector.\n",
        "\n",
        "For $f(x,y)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x,y)=\\langle f_x(x,y), f_y(x,y)\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For $f(x,y,z)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x,y,z)=\\langle f_x(x,y,z), f_y(x,y,z), f_z(x,y,z)\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "More generally, for $f(x_1,\n",
        "\\ldots,x_n)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x_1,\\ldots,x_n)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\left\\langle\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x_1},\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x_2},\n",
        "\\ldots,\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x_n}\n",
        "\\right\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The symbol $\\nabla$ is pronounced **del** or **nabla**.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.6: Gradient of a two-variable function\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=\\sin(xy)+e^y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x=y\\cos(xy),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y=x\\cos(xy)+e^y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x,y)=\\langle y\\cos(xy), x\\cos(xy)+e^y\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(0,1)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(0,1)=\\langle 1,e\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 8.7: Gradient of a three-variable function\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y,z)=xyz.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x=yz,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y=xz,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_z=xy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x,y,z)=\\langle yz,xz,xy\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(1,2,3)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(1,2,3)=\\langle 6,3,2\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.10 The gradient and level curves\n",
        "\n",
        "Level curves have equations\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=c.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The gradient $\\nabla f$ is perpendicular to the level curve at points where $\\nabla f\\ne 0$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Why? Suppose $r(t)=\\langle x(t),y(t)\\rangle$ is a curve that stays on the level curve $f(x,y)=c$. Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x(t),y(t))=c.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Differentiating with respect to $t$ gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f(x(t),y(t))\\cdot r'(t)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The vector $r'(t)$ is tangent to the level curve. Therefore the gradient is perpendicular to the tangent direction.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important title='Geometric meaning of the gradient'}\n",
        "The gradient points normal to level curves and level surfaces. It tells us which direction cuts most directly across the contours.\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "6d32af3f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
