      "source": [
        "## 8.14 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 1: Differentiating every variable at once'}\n",
        "When computing $f_x$, only $x$ varies. All other variables are constants. For example, if $f(x,y)=x^2y$, then $f_x=2xy$, not $2xy+x^2$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 2: Confusing partial derivatives with total change'}\n",
        "The partial derivative $f_x(a,b)$ measures change only in the $x$ direction. It does not describe motion along an arbitrary path unless the path moves only in the $x$ direction.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 3: Forgetting to normalize a direction vector'}\n",
        "In the directional derivative formula $D_u f=\\nabla f\\cdot u$, the vector $u$ must be a unit vector. If a problem gives a nonunit direction vector, divide by its length first.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 4: Assuming mixed partials are always equal'}\n",
        "Mixed partials are equal under hypotheses such as continuity near the point. For standard smooth examples this is usually true, but the theorem has a condition.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.15 Chapter exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "### Conceptual questions\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Explain in words what $f_x(a,b)$ means.\n",
        "2. Explain why $f_x(a,b)$ is the slope of a trace of the surface $z=f(x,y)$.\n",
        "3. Explain the difference between $f_x(a,b)$ and $f_y(a,b)$.\n",
        "4. Why is a partial derivative not the same thing as a directional derivative in every direction?\n",
        "5. Explain why $\\nabla f$ is perpendicular to a level curve.\n",
        "6. In an image, what do large values of $|I_x|$ and $|I_y|$ usually indicate?\n",
        "7. In a loss function $L(\\theta_1,\\theta_2)$, what does $\\partial L/\\partial \\theta_1$ mean?\n",
        "8. Explain why the gradient is useful even when the function has many variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Skill problems\n",
        "\n",
        "9. Find $f_x$ and $f_y$ for $f(x,y)=x^2y+3xy^2-y$.\n",
        "10. Find $f_x$ and $f_y$ for $f(x,y)=e^{xy}+\\ln(x+y)$ on its domain.\n",
        "11. Find $f_x$ and $f_y$ for $f(x,y)=\\cos(x^2+y^2)$.\n",
        "12. Find $\\nabla f(1,2)$ for $f(x,y)=x^3y+y^2$.\n",
        "13. Find $\\nabla f(0,1)$ for $f(x,y)=\\sin(xy)+e^y$.\n",
        "14. Find $\\nabla f(1,2,3)$ for $f(x,y,z)=x^2y+yz^3$.\n",
        "15. Find all four second partial derivatives of $f(x,y)=x^2+xy^3+\\sin(xy)$.\n",
        "16. Verify Clairaut's theorem for $f(x,y)=e^{xy}+x^2y^3$.\n",
        "17. Estimate $f_x(2,1)$ using $f(2,1)=5.0$ and $f(2.1,1)=5.32$.\n",
        "18. Estimate $f_y(2,1)$ using $f(2,1)=5.0$ and $f(2,1.2)=4.7$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Applied and computational problems\n",
        "\n",
        "19. Let $H(x,y)=1100-2x^2-y^2$ model the height of a hill in meters. Compute $H_x$ and $H_y$, and interpret them.\n",
        "20. For the same hill, compute $\\nabla H(10,20)$ and explain what the signs of its components mean.\n",
        "21. Let $T(x,y,z)=xe^y+0.5z^2$. Compute $\\nabla T(1,0,3)$.\n",
        "22. Let $I$ be an image intensity function. Explain how finite differences approximate $I_x$ and $I_y$.\n",
        "23. For least-squares regression with two parameters, derive the gradient of\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(\\beta_0,\\beta_1)=\\sum_{i=1}^m \\left(y_i-(\\beta_0+\\beta_1x_i)\\right)^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "24. Write Python code to approximate $\\nabla f(1,2)$ for $f(x,y)=x^3+x^2\\sin y-xe^y$ using centered differences.\n",
        "25. Generate a contour plot of $f(x,y)=x^2+4y^2$ and draw gradient vectors at several points.\n",
        "26. Use Python to compute numerical gradients on a grid for $f(x,y)=\\sin x\\cos y$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Challenge problems\n",
        "\n",
        "27. Let $f(x,y)=\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}$. Show that $f_x(0,0)$ and $f_y(0,0)$ exist, but explain why this does not mean the surface has a tangent plane at the origin.\n",
        "28. Find a function for which $f_x$ and $f_y$ exist at the origin but the function is not continuous at the origin.\n",
        "29. Suppose $f(x,y)=g(x^2+y^2)$ for a differentiable single-variable function $g$. Find $\\nabla f$.\n",
        "30. Suppose $f(x,y)=h(ax+by)$ for a differentiable single-variable function $h$. Find $\\nabla f$ and describe the direction of the gradient.\n",
        "31. Let $f(x,y,z)=F(x^2+y^2+z^2)$. Find $\\nabla f$ and describe its direction geometrically.\n",
        "32. In a high-dimensional model, the gradient has one component per parameter. Explain why this makes gradient methods scalable compared with searching every direction separately.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.16 Python lab and interactive page\n",
        "\n",
        "The Python lab for this chapter focuses on numerical and visual differentiation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- estimating partial derivatives from function values;\n",
        "- comparing forward, backward, and centered differences;\n",
        "- plotting coordinate traces of surfaces;\n",
        "- visualizing gradients on contour plots;\n",
        "- computing image gradients;\n",
        "- computing gradients of least-squares losses.\n",
        "\n",
        "Open the resources here:\n",
        "\n",
        "- [Chapter 8 Python lab](../labs/MATH2321_Chapter08_Partial_Derivatives_and_the_Gradient.ipynb)\n",
        "- [Chapter 8 interactive HTML page](../htmls/chapter-08.html)\n",
        "\n",
        "## Chapter summary\n",
        "\n",
        "Partial derivatives are the coordinate-direction derivatives of a multivariable function. They are ordinary derivatives applied to slices of the function. For $f(x,y)$, the two first partial derivatives are $f_x$ and $f_y$. For a function of $n$ variables, there are $n$ first partial derivatives.\n",
        "\n",
        "The gradient packages these partial derivatives into a vector:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla f=\\left\\langle\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x_1},\n",
        "\\ldots,\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x_n}\n",
        "\\right\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This vector is perpendicular to level sets and contains the first-order sensitivity information of the function. In modern applications, the gradient is the basic object behind numerical differentiation, image processing, optimization, maximum likelihood, backpropagation, and gradient-based learning."
      ],
      "id": "6ce2d48a"
    }
